<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="503" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,429,562]" pageId="2" pageNumber="503">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,429,454]" pageId="2" pageNumber="503">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Chondrillida in which the choanocyte chambers are tubular, branched and wide mouthed. Larvae are incubated disphaerulae (a larval form found only in 
<taxonomicName box="[741,852,465,489]" class="Demospongiae" family="Halisarcidae" genus="Halisarca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chondrosida" pageId="2" pageNumber="503" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[741,852,465,489]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="503">Halisarca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) with simple undifferentiated histology and cilia of uniform length. Skeleton is composed of fibrillar collagen only, there are no fibrous or mineral elements present; ectosomal and subectosomal collagen is highly organised and structurally diversified (
<bibRefCitation author="Ereskovsky" box="[1116,1378,537,562]" pageId="2" pageNumber="503" refString="Ereskovsky, A. V., Lavrov, D. V., Boury-Esnault, N. &amp; Vacelet, J. (2011) Molecular and morphological description of a new species of Halisarca (Demospongiae: Halisarcida) from Mediterranean Sea and a redescription of the type species Halisarca dujardini. Zootaxa, 2768, 5 - 31." type="journal article" year="2011">
Ereskovsky 
<emphasis box="[1255,1304,537,561]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="503">et al</emphasis>
. 2011
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
